      "message": "\u003e \u003e object_path can throw an exception if the path isn\u0027t valid in the passed in string.\n\u003e \n\u003e How so? There is no check, the string is directly assigned.\n\nFair point.  For some reason I thought there were more checks on construction.  I think I got mixed up on your desire for an \"always valid\" object_path class.  If we agree we\u0027re not chasing that anymore, this patch seems fine.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e ```cpp\n\u003e   struct string_path_wrapper\n\u003e   {\n\u003e       std::string str;\n\u003e   \n\u003e       string_path_wrapper() \u003d default;\n\u003e       string_path_wrapper(const string_path_wrapper\u0026) \u003d default;\n\u003e       string_path_wrapper\u0026 operator\u003d(const string_path_wrapper\u0026) \u003d default;\n\u003e       string_path_wrapper(string_path_wrapper\u0026\u0026) \u003d default;\n\u003e       string_path_wrapper\u0026 operator\u003d(string_path_wrapper\u0026\u0026) \u003d default;\n\u003e       ~string_path_wrapper() \u003d default;\n\u003e   \n\u003e       string_path_wrapper(const std::string\u0026 str_in) : str(str_in) {}\n\u003e       string_path_wrapper(std::string\u0026\u0026 str_in) : str(std::move(str_in)) {}\n\u003e ```\n\u003e \n\u003e I am looking at `string_path_wrapper(const std::string\u0026 str_in) : str(str_in) {}` here.\n\u003e \n\u003e \u003e yeah, you are correct, but the implicit conversion could throw, right?\n\u003e \n\u003e I\u0027m not super familiar with implicit conversions but if it calls the `object_path` constructor, that just assigns the string. `object_path` does not contribute anything new in terms of exceptions.\n\nYep, you did the right analysis.  I was replying to your other patch and got confused.",
