      "message": "\u003e If we\u0027re not adding safety anywhere,\n\nIn your other response you wrote\n\n\u003e object_path can throw an exception if the path isn\u0027t valid in the passed in string.\n\nSo either using `object_path` gives us exceptions in cases where there were none before (i don\u0027t think so), increasing the safety, or, it does not, in which case the change is safe to do and improves readability (intent to pass object path).\n\n\u003e Code more readable, maybe.  More robust, I\u0027m not sure I see how?\n\nIf we use a simpler type with less API surface, IMO that makes the code more robust and easier to review / change.\n\nThen we can be more confident that throughout the code only the supported operations are performed on the object path.\n\nWe can only be sure of it if the `str` member of `object_path` were private, but one step at a time.\n\n\u003e Because it exists, and has existed prior to object_path,\n\nYes, a good sign we should change it. Now that we have the `object_path`, we can apply it everywhere we want to represent object paths.",
